SECTION 2 — NAMING CONVENTIONS
================================================================================

PYTHON FILES
All Python files must use snake_case.
Correct:   student_service.py, enrollment_repository.py, course_schema.py
Incorrect: StudentService.py, enrollmentRepository.py

PYTHON CLASSES
All Python classes must use PascalCase.
Correct:   class StudentService, class CourseRepository, class EnrollmentCreateSchema
Incorrect: class student_service, class courseRepository

PYDANTIC SCHEMAS
Every Pydantic model class must be suffixed with "Schema".
Correct:   StudentCreateSchema, StudentResponseSchema, StudentUpdateSchema
           CourseCreateSchema, CourseResponseSchema, CourseUpdateSchema
           EnrollmentCreateSchema, EnrollmentResponseSchema
           PaginationMetaSchema, PaginatedResponseSchema
Incorrect: StudentCreate, StudentResponse, CreateStudent

SQLALCHEMY MODELS
SQLAlchemy ORM model classes must NOT use any suffix.
Correct:   Student, Course, Enrollment
Incorrect: StudentModel, CourseORM, EnrollmentTable

REACT FILES AND COMPONENTS
React component files must use PascalCase.
Correct:   StudentCard.jsx, EnrollForm.jsx, ErrorBanner.jsx
Incorrect: studentCard.jsx, enroll_form.jsx

Non-component JS files must use camelCase.
Correct:   client.js, envelopeParser.js, errorMessages.js
Incorrect: Client.js, envelope_parser.js

VARIABLES AND FUNCTIONS
Python: snake_case for all variables and function names.
JavaScript: camelCase for all variables and function names.

DATABASE COLUMNS AND JSON FIELDS
All database column names and all JSON field names must be snake_case.
They must exactly match the column names in DATA-MODEL.md.
Permitted fields for students:   id, first_name, last_name, email, enrollment_date, is_active, created_at, updated_at
Permitted fields for courses:    id, name, description, is_active, created_at, updated_at
Permitted fields for enrollments: id, student_id, course_id, enrolled_at, created_at

URL PATHS
All API route paths must use kebab-case for multi-word segments.
All routes must be prefixed with /api/v1/.
Correct:   /api/v1/students, /api/v1/students/{student_id}/courses
Incorrect: /api/v1/Students, /students, /api/v1/student_courses


================================================================================
SECTION 3 — RESPONSE ENVELOPE ENFORCEMENT
================================================================================

RULE: Every route handler in every router file must return responses exclusively
through the envelope builder in core/envelope.py. No route handler may return a
raw Pydantic model, a raw dict, or a JSONResponse constructed inline.

SUCCESS ENVELOPE SHAPE (all fields required):
{
  "success": true,
  "data": <object or array>,
  "message": "<human-readable string>",
  "meta": <object, list endpoints only, omit on single-resource and write responses>
}

META SHAPE (list endpoints only):
{
  "page": <integer, 1-indexed>,
  "page_size": <integer>,
  "total": <integer, total matching records across all pages>
}

ERROR ENVELOPE SHAPE (all fields required):
{
  "success": false,
  "error": {
    "code": "<SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE>",
    "message": "<human-readable string, safe to display in UI>",
    "field": "<field name string for 422 errors, null for all other errors>"
  }
}

RULE: "meta" must be omitted entirely from single-resource and write responses
(POST create, PUT update, DELETE deactivate/unenroll). It must be present on
all GET list responses.

RULE: "field" in the error envelope must be null for 401, 403, 404, and 409
responses. It must identify the offending field name for 422 responses.

RULE: The envelope builder must be called inside a single global exception
handler registered in main.py. Individual routers must not contain try/except
blocks that construct error responses directly.

RULE: HTTP status codes in use in this project:
201 — resource created successfully
200 — read, update, or deactivation succeeded
401 — missing or invalid JWT
403 — valid JWT, insufficient role
404 — UUID not found
409 — business rule conflict (duplicate, blocked deactivation)
422 — validation failure or inactive entity rule violation


================================================================================
SECTION 4 — LAYER RESPONSIBILITY AND STRICT LOGIC SEPARATION
================================================================================

ROUTER LAYER RULES
A router function is permitted to do exactly three things:
  1. Validate the request shape via a Pydantic schema (Pydantic returns 422 automatically).
  2. Enforce the role permission check (call the role dependency; return 403 on failure).
  3. Call the corresponding service method and pass the result to the envelope builder.

RULE: A router function must never contain an if-statement that represents a
business rule. The only conditionals permitted in a router are those required
by the role dependency check.

RULE: A router function must never import or reference SQLAlchemy, a repository
class, or a database session object.

RULE: A router function must never construct an error response directly. All
errors are raised as domain exceptions in the service layer and caught by the
global exception handler.

RULE: A router function must never call another router function.

SERVICE LAYER RULES
The service layer owns all business logic. Every acceptance criterion from
BACKLOG.md that describes a business rule is implemented in a service method.

RULE: A service method must never import SQLAlchemy, construct a query, or
reference a database session object directly. All data access is delegated
to a repository method.

RULE: A service method must raise a typed domain exception from
core/exceptions.py when a business rule is violated. It must never return
an error shape or set an HTTP status code directly.

RULE: Service classes must accept their repository dependencies via constructor
injection. Hardcoding a repository instantiation inside a service method is
prohibited. This enables unit testing with mock repositories.

RULE: Service method signatures must be async. No synchronous service methods.

BUSINESS RULES THAT MUST LIVE IN THE SERVICE LAYER (not routers, not repos):
- Duplicate email check on student create and student update (FR-02)
- Future enrollment date rejection (FR-04)
- Active student check before enrollment (FR-16, AC-11-4)
- Active course check before enrollment (FR-17, AC-11-6)
- Duplicate enrollment check (FR-18, AC-11-7)
- Active enrollment guard before course deactivation (FR-14, AC-10-4)

REPOSITORY LAYER RULES
The repository layer is the only layer permitted to import SQLAlchemy or
issue database queries.

RULE: A repository method must return a plain domain model object or a list
of plain domain model objects. It must never return a raw SQLAlchemy ORM
instance to the service layer. Map ORM objects to domain models before return.

RULE: A repository method that lists records must apply is_active = TRUE
filtering by default. The base repository class in repositories/base.py must
enforce this default so individual methods cannot accidentally omit it.

RULE: A repository method that lists records must apply the default sort:
  - students and courses: created_at DESC
  - enrollments: enrolled_at DESC
This sort must be applied in the repository, not in the service or router.

RULE: Repository methods must be async. No synchronous repository methods.

RULE: Repository method names must express intent, not SQL mechanics.
Correct:   get_by_email, deactivate, list_paginated, get_by_student_id
Incorrect: select_where_email, update_is_active, run_query

RULE: The repository layer must catch SQLAlchemy unique constraint violations
and re-raise them as the appropriate typed domain exception from
core/exceptions.py before they propagate to the service layer.

FRONTEND API CLIENT RULES
The Axios instance in src/api/client.js is the only location where the
base URL and JWT Bearer token are configured.

RULE: No component or page file may construct a fetch or axios call directly.
All API calls must go through the functions in src/api/.

RULE: The frontend must never contain business logic. All validation decisions
are delegated to the backend. Client-side field validation for UX purposes is
permitted only if it mirrors a backend constraint exactly.

RULE: The frontend reads all API responses through envelopeParser.js. No
component may directly access response.data.data or response.data.error
without going through the shared parser.


================================================================================
SECTION 5 — EXCEPTIONS AND ERROR GOVERNANCE
================================================================================

ALL PERMITTED EXCEPTION CLASSES (must be defined in core/exceptions.py only):

DomainException          — base class; all custom exceptions inherit from this
ResourceNotFoundException  — maps to 404 RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND
DuplicateEmailException    — maps to 409 EMAIL_ALREADY_EXISTS
EnrollmentConflictException — maps to 409 ENROLLMENT_ALREADY_EXISTS
CourseHasActiveEnrollmentsException — maps to 409 COURSE_HAS_ACTIVE_ENROLLMENTS
ValidationException        — maps to 422 VALIDATION_ERROR; carries field: str attribute
StudentInactiveException   — maps to 422 STUDENT_INACTIVE; carries field: "student_id"
CourseInactiveException    — maps to 422 COURSE_INACTIVE; carries field: "course_id"
UnauthorizedException      — maps to 401 UNAUTHORIZED
ForbiddenException         — maps to 403 FORBIDDEN

RULE: Raising a plain Python Exception, ValueError, KeyError, or any built-in
exception to signal a domain error is prohibited. All domain errors must be
raised using one of the typed exception classes above.

RULE: All domain exception classes must carry a "code" attribute set to the
exact SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE value from the API-CONTRACTS.md error registry.
The global exception handler reads this attribute to populate error.code
in the response envelope.

PERMITTED ERROR CODES (exact strings, no variation permitted):
UNAUTHORIZED
FORBIDDEN
RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND
EMAIL_ALREADY_EXISTS
ENROLLMENT_ALREADY_EXISTS
COURSE_HAS_ACTIVE_ENROLLMENTS
VALIDATION_ERROR
STUDENT_INACTIVE
COURSE_INACTIVE

RULE: The global exception handler in main.py is the single location that maps
domain exceptions to HTTP status codes and constructs error envelopes. No other
file may perform this mapping.

RULE: Pydantic validation failures (422) are handled by the existing FastAPI
exception handler override. The override must format the response to match
the standard error envelope shape with code: "VALIDATION_ERROR" and
field: <first failing field name>.

FRONTEND ERROR HANDLING RULES
RULE: The frontend must map every SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE error code to a
human-readable display string in src/utils/errorMessages.js.
RULE: No component may display a raw error code string or a raw Python
traceback to the user under any circumstance.
RULE: If error.code is STUDENT_INACTIVE or COURSE_INACTIVE, the frontend
must surface a message that identifies the deactivated entity by name, not
by UUID.


================================================================================
SECTION 6 — TYPE AND VALIDATION STANDARDS
================================================================================

EMAIL FIELDS
RULE: Every Pydantic schema field that represents an email address must use
the EmailStr type from pydantic[email]. Using plain str for an email field
is prohibited.
Correct:   email: EmailStr
Incorrect: email: str

UUID FIELDS
RULE: Every Pydantic schema field that represents a UUID (id, student_id,
course_id) must use the UUID type from Python's uuid module, not str.
Correct:   id: UUID, student_id: UUID
Incorrect: id: str, student_id: str

RULE: Every path parameter that accepts a UUID must be typed as UUID in the
FastAPI route signature. FastAPI will automatically return 422 VALIDATION_ERROR
with the offending field name if a non-RFC-4122 value is supplied.
Correct:   async def get_student(student_id: UUID, ...)
Incorrect: async def get_student(student_id: str, ...)

DATE FIELDS
RULE: enrollment_date must use Python's datetime.date type in all Pydantic
schemas. It must be serialized to YYYY-MM-DD in all JSON responses.

TIMESTAMP FIELDS
RULE: created_at and updated_at must use datetime with timezone=True in all
Pydantic schemas. They must be serialized to ISO 8601 UTC format
(YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.sssZ) in all JSON responses.

BOOLEAN FIELDS
RULE: is_active must use Python's bool type. It must serialize to JSON
true / false (lowercase). Do not serialize as 0/1 or "true"/"false".

PAGINATION FIELDS
RULE: page and page_size query parameters must have the following defaults
and constraints enforced at the router level via Pydantic Query annotations:
  page:      default=1, ge=1
  page_size: default=20, ge=1, le=100

SQLALCHEMY COLUMN TYPES
RULE: id columns must use sqlalchemy.dialects.postgresql.UUID with
as_uuid=True and server_default=text("gen_random_uuid()").
RULE: created_at and updated_at must use DateTime(timezone=True) with
server_default=func.now(). updated_at must also carry onupdate=func.now().
RULE: is_active must use Boolean with nullable=False and default=True.
RULE: email must carry a UniqueConstraint at the table level, not only
a column-level unique=True.
RULE: The enrollments table must carry a UniqueConstraint on
(student_id, course_id) defined at the table level in __table_args__.


================================================================================
SECTION 7 — ASYNC AND CONCURRENCY STANDARDS
================================================================================

RULE: All route handler functions must be declared with async def.
Synchronous route handlers are prohibited.

RULE: All service methods must be declared with async def.

RULE: All repository methods must be declared with async def.

RULE: The SQLAlchemy session must be created via an async session factory
using AsyncSession from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio. The synchronous Session
must not be used anywhere in the codebase.

RULE: Database sessions must be injected into repository methods via
FastAPI's Depends() mechanism. Sessions must never be instantiated directly
inside a service or repository method body.

RULE: await must be used on every async database call. Unawaited coroutines
are a silent failure mode and are treated as a blocking bug.

RULE: The UNIQUE(student_id, course_id) constraint on the enrollments table
is the final race-condition guard for concurrent duplicate enrollment attempts.
The service-layer duplicate check is the first guard. Both guards must be
present. The repository must catch the DB unique violation and raise
EnrollmentConflictException so the 409 response is returned to both
concurrent callers.


