SECTION 8 — AUTHENTICATION AND MIDDLEWARE
================================================================================

RULE: JWT validation must occur in middleware (core/middleware.py) before
any request reaches a router. No router function may perform JWT validation.

RULE: The middleware must extract the role claim from the validated JWT and
attach it to the request state as request.state.role.

RULE: The middleware must generate a unique request ID (UUID v4) for every
incoming request and attach it to the request state as request.state.request_id.
This ID must appear in all log lines for that request.

RULE: If the JWT is missing, malformed, or expired, the middleware must return
a 401 response using the standard error envelope before the request proceeds
to any router or service. No business logic may execute on an unauthenticated
request.

RULE: Role enforcement is a two-layer system.
  Layer 1: Middleware validates the token is present and well-formed.
  Layer 2: A FastAPI role dependency on each protected route checks
           request.state.role against the permitted roles for that endpoint.
The permitted role sets are:
  admin only:        POST /students, PUT /students/{id}, DELETE /students/{id}
                     POST /courses,  PUT /courses/{id},  DELETE /courses/{id}
                     DELETE /students/{id}/courses/{course_id}
  admin and staff:   GET /students, GET /students/{id}
                     GET /courses,  GET /courses/{id}
                     POST /students/{id}/courses
                     GET  /students/{id}/courses

RULE: The role dependency function must be defined once in core/security.py
and reused via Depends() on every protected route. It must not be duplicated
or reimplemented per-router.

RULE: Sensitive data — JWT token strings, Authorization header values,
passwords, and any credential material — must never appear in log output
at any log level.


================================================================================
SECTION 9 — LOGGING STANDARDS
================================================================================

RULE: All logging must use Python's standard logging module configured in
core/logging.py. print() statements are prohibited in production code paths.

RULE: Every incoming HTTP request must be logged at INFO level. The log
line must include: timestamp, request_id, HTTP method, path, and response
status code. It must NOT include: Authorization header, JWT token, request
body content, email addresses, or any other PII.

RULE: Every unhandled exception and every domain exception that results in
a 4xx or 5xx response must be logged at ERROR level with a full stack trace.
The log line must include: request_id, error code, and exception type.
It must NOT include field values that may contain PII.

RULE: Log levels in use:
  DEBUG   — local development only; must be disabled in staging and production
  INFO    — request lifecycle events, service method entry/exit in development
  WARNING — recoverable issues, deprecated usage
  ERROR   — all exceptions that generate a 4xx or 5xx response

RULE: The PII filter defined in core/logging.py must scrub the following
patterns from all log output at all levels: email addresses, JWT tokens,
Authorization header values, and any field matching the name "password".


